        "Step-by-Step Rescue Scenarios")
            text="STEP-BY-STEP RESCUE SCENARIOS
=============================

SCENARIO 1: FORGOTTEN ROOT PASSWORD
------------------------------------
METHOD A - Via Chroot:
  1. Boot from live USB
  2. sudo mount /dev/sdXY /mnt
  3. for i in dev dev/pts proc sys run; do sudo mount -B /\$i /mnt/\$i; done
  4. sudo chroot /mnt
  5. passwd root
  6. passwd <username>
  7. exit && sudo umount -R /mnt

METHOD B - Via GRUB (systemd):
  1. At GRUB, press 'e' to edit
  2. Find line starting with 'linux'
  3. Add: init=/bin/bash
  4. Press Ctrl+X or F10
  5. mount -o remount,rw /
  6. passwd root
  7. exec /sbin/init

SCENARIO 2: BROKEN APT/DPKG
---------------------------
STEP 1 - Clear locks:
  sudo rm /var/lib/dpkg/lock*
  sudo rm /var/lib/apt/lists/lock
  sudo rm /var/cache/apt/archives/lock

STEP 2 - Reconfigure:
  sudo dpkg --configure -a

STEP 3 - Fix dependencies:
  sudo apt update --fix-missing
  sudo apt install -f
  sudo apt --fix-broken install

STEP 4 - If still broken:
  sudo dpkg --remove --force-remove-reinstreq <package>
  sudo apt clean
  sudo apt update

SCENARIO 3: FULL ROOT PARTITION
-------------------------------
EMERGENCY ACCESS:
  1. CTRL+ALT+F2 (TTY, may work when GUI fails)
  2. Login as root

QUICK CLEANUP:
  sudo apt clean
  sudo journalctl --vacuum-size=50M
  sudo rm -rf /tmp/*
  sudo find /var/log -name '*.gz' -delete
  sudo truncate -s 0 /var/log/syslog
  sudo truncate -s 0 /var/log/kern.log

FIND LARGE FILES:
  sudo du -ah / 2>/dev/null | sort -hr | head -50
  sudo find / -xdev -type f -size +100M

IF CANNOT LOGIN (from live USB):
  sudo mount /dev/sdXY /mnt
  sudo rm -rf /mnt/var/cache/apt/archives/*.deb
  sudo rm -rf /mnt/tmp/*

SCENARIO 4: GRUB COMPLETELY MISSING
------------------------------------
FROM LIVE USB:
  1. Mount root: sudo mount /dev/sdXY /mnt
  2. Mount EFI (if UEFI):
     sudo mount /dev/sda1 /mnt/boot/efi
  3. Bind mount:
     for i in dev dev/pts proc sys run; do sudo mount -B /\$i /mnt/\$i; done
  4. Chroot: sudo chroot /mnt
  5. Reinstall GRUB:
     # For BIOS:
     grub-install /dev/sda
     # For UEFI:
     grub-install --target=x86_64-efi --efi-directory=/boot/efi
  6. update-grub
  7. exit && sudo umount -R /mnt

SCENARIO 5: KERNEL PANIC ON BOOT
--------------------------------
DIAGNOSE:
  - Note the panic message (take photo)
  - Common causes: driver issues, filesystem corruption

FIX - Boot older kernel:
  1. Hold SHIFT at boot to show GRUB menu
  2. Select 'Advanced options'
  3. Choose an older kernel version

FIX - Rebuild initramfs:
  1. Boot from live USB
  2. Chroot into system
  3. update-initramfs -u -k all
  4. (or) dracut --force --regenerate-all
  5. Reboot

FIX - Disable problematic module:
  1. At GRUB, edit kernel line
  2. Add: modprobe.blacklist=<module_name>

SCENARIO 6: LUKS ENCRYPTED SYSTEM WON'T BOOT
--------------------------------------------
FROM LIVE USB:
  1. Open LUKS: sudo cryptsetup luksOpen /dev/sda3 crypt_root
     (Enter your passphrase)
  2. If LVM: sudo vgchange -ay
  3. Mount: sudo mount /dev/mapper/vg0-root /mnt
  4. Mount boot: sudo mount /dev/sda2 /mnt/boot
  5. Bind mount API filesystems
  6. Chroot and fix issue
  7. Regenerate initramfs: update-initramfs -u -k all
  8. Exit and close: sudo cryptsetup luksClose crypt_root

SCENARIO 7: X SERVER / GUI WON'T START
--------------------------------------
DIAGNOSE:
  CTRL+ALT+F2 (switch to TTY)
  cat /var/log/Xorg.0.log | grep -E '(EE|WW)'
  journalctl -u gdm (or lightdm, sddm)

QUICK FIXES:
  sudo dpkg-reconfigure gdm3
  sudo apt install --reinstall xserver-xorg-core
  sudo apt install --reinstall nvidia-driver-XXX  # If NVIDIA

RESET DISPLAY MANAGER:
  sudo systemctl restart gdm3

SAFE MODE (nomodeset):
  1. At GRUB, edit kernel line
  2. Add: nomodeset
  3. Boot and fix driver

SCENARIO 8: SYSTEM WON'T SHUTDOWN/REBOOT
----------------------------------------
FORCE SHUTDOWN:
  echo 1 > /proc/sys/kernel/sysrq
  echo o > /proc/sysrq-trigger              # Poweroff
  # Or: echo b > /proc/sysrq-trigger        # Reboot (unsafe)

SAFE SYSRQ SEQUENCE (REISUB):
  Alt+SysRq+R  (Raw keyboard)
  Alt+SysRq+E  (Terminate all)
  Alt+SysRq+I  (Kill all)
  Alt+SysRq+S  (Sync)
  Alt+SysRq+U  (Unmount)
  Alt+SysRq+B  (Reboot)

SCENARIO 9: SSH INTO BROKEN SYSTEM (initramfs)
----------------------------------------------
SETUP (before disaster):
  sudo apt install dropbear-initramfs
  Edit /etc/dropbear-initramfs/authorized_keys
  sudo update-initramfs -u

WHEN SYSTEM HANGS AT INITRAMFS:
  ssh root@<IP>
  # You're in initramfs, can unlock LUKS manually:
  cryptsetup luksOpen /dev/sda3 crypt_root
  exit

SCENARIO 10: RECOVER FROM BAD FSTAB
-----------------------------------
BOOT FAILS DUE TO INCORRECT FSTAB:
  1. At boot failure, you may get emergency shell
  2. mount -o remount,rw /
  3. nano /etc/fstab (comment out bad line with #)
  4. reboot

FROM LIVE USB:
  sudo mount /dev/sdXY /mnt
  sudo nano /mnt/etc/fstab
  # Comment problematic lines
  # Verify UUIDs: blkid
  sudo umount /mnt
  
REGENERATE FSTAB HINTS:
  blkid | awk '{print \$1, \$2}'"
            ;;
    esac

